To carry out its purpose and in compliance with the Affordable Care Act, the SHOP Exchange navigator program, with respect only to qualified plans offered in the SHOP Exchange, shall provide comprehensive consumer assistance services, including:
conducting education and outreach to small employers;
distributing information about the SHOP Exchange, including information about:
options with respect to employer and employee choice;
procedures for enrolling in qualified plans; and
the availability of applicable tax credits;
facilitating:
qualified plan selection, based on the needs of the employee;
application processes;
enrollment;
renewals; and
disenrollment;
conducting eligibility determinations and redeterminations for tax credits;
providing referrals to appropriate agencies, including the Attorney General's Health Education and Advocacy Unit and the Administration, for applicants and enrollees with grievances, complaints, or questions;
providing all information and services in a manner that is culturally and linguistically appropriate and ensures accessibility for individuals with disabilities; and
providing ongoing support with respect to the functions set forth in this section, including eligibility and enrollment and disenrollment in and renewal of qualified plans offered in the SHOP Exchange.

A SHOP Exchange navigator:
shall hold a SHOP Exchange navigator license issued under subsection (d) of this section;
may not be required to hold an insurance producer license;
shall be engaged by and receive compensation only through the SHOP Exchange;
may not receive compensation from or otherwise be affiliated with a carrier, an insurance producer, a third-party administrator, or any other person connected to the insurance industry; and
shall complete and comply with any ongoing requirements of the training program established under subsection (h) of this section.

To qualify for a SHOP Exchange navigator license, an applicant:
shall be of good character and trustworthy;
shall be at least 18 years old;
shall pass a written examination given by the Commissioner under this subsection; and
may not have committed any act that the Commissioner finds would warrant suspension or revocation of a license under subsection (e) of this section.

The Commissioner may suspend, revoke, or refuse to renew or reinstate a SHOP Exchange navigator license after notice and opportunity for a hearing under §§ 2-210 through 2-214 of this article, if the licensee:
has willfully violated this article or any regulation adopted under this article;
has intentionally misrepresented or concealed a material fact in the application for the license;
has obtained the license by misrepresentation, concealment, or other fraud;
has engaged in fraudulent or dishonest practices in conducting activities under the license;
has misappropriated, converted, or unlawfully withheld money in conducting activities under the license;
has failed or refused to pay over on demand money that belongs to a person entitled to the money;
has willfully and materially misrepresented the provisions of a qualified plan;
has been convicted of a felony, a crime of moral turpitude, or any criminal offense involving dishonesty or breach of trust;
has failed an examination required by this article or regulations adopted under this article;
has forged another's name on an application for a qualified plan or on any other document in conducting activities under the license;
has otherwise shown a lack of trustworthiness or competence to act as a SHOP Exchange navigator; or
has willfully failed to comply with or violated a proper order or subpoena of the Commissioner.
